"{\"content\":{\"body\":\"Hey Crypto Club ğŸ‘‹\\n\\nIn my quest to explore DeFi, the first step was to recognize that everything I will do comes with some risk âš–ï¸ There are different kinds of risks from investing in cryptocurrencies that go nowhere, to being liquidated when you borrow against a volatile asset, to the infamous **[rug pull](https://coinmarketcap.com/alexandria/glossary/rug-pull)** ğŸ¤¦â€â™‚ï¸ Now all investing comes with risks, but in such an unregulated space as cryptocurrency, sometimes youâ€™re just gambling.\\n\\nThis post is about how I gambled and lost ğŸ°\\n\\nYou see, lately Iâ€™ve been experimenting with the Ethereum sidechain **[Polygon](https://decrypt.co/resources/what-is-polygon-matic-and-why-it-matters-for-ethereum)** â€” more on that coming soon. This unique project aims to help scale Ethereum by offering a way to bridge from the Ethereum Mainnet onto the sidechain where transactions can cost as little as a thousandth of a penny ğŸ˜² You could think of this a bit like Bitcoinâ€™s Lightning Network but with DeFi.\\n\\nAs youâ€™ll recall from **[my last Crypto Misadventure](https://www.buymeacoffee.com/thumbsupfinance/crypto-misadventures-1)**, I found gas fees on Ethereum (the fees paid to the validators to write the transaction to the block) to be prohibitively expensive for someone like myself with so little capital to invest in this space ğŸ˜… For that reason, Polygon was a natural fit for someone like me to learn all about DeFi without hemorrhaging money ğŸ’¸\\n\\nSpeaking of which, Iâ€™ve just set another goal on the blog. When I reach my next $100 of support, Iâ€™m going to do a post, video included, all about how you can try out Polygon for yourself. And in that post, Iâ€™ll talk about some of the safest ways to explore DeFi including what Iâ€™m doing, and mistakes Iâ€™ve made ğŸ˜ª I largely focus on established, secured, and audited projects, with high total value locked (TVL) as these are great for beginners and serious investors alike, but there is also some fun to be had elsewhere, if youâ€™re willing to gamble ğŸ°\\n\\nFirst things first, I want to say that if you are worried that I am gambling away every dollar I have, fret not! Of the around $100 I have invested into Polygon DeFi so far, the vast majority is in safe vehicles ğŸ’° In fact, much of this money was deposited to serve as interest bearing collateral to take loans against, and that loan money was itself deposited into stable investments with high APY (Iâ€™ll explain more in the aforementioned bonus post) ğŸ I did however take about $30 of my own money to experiment with high risk, high reward yield farming opportunities ğŸ¤‘ My thinking was if I could find something that was truly as good as it seemed, I might be willing to invest $100. After all, in a post-pandemic world I could certainly see myself wasting $100 on the occasional night out ğŸ‰\\n\\nWith all that said, letâ€™s get into it.\\n\\n![](https://miro.medium.com/max/1400/0\\\\*R3YD70Jyk3xXF9bM.jpg)\\n\\nIf youâ€™ve been following for long, youâ€™ll know that Iâ€™m a **[big fan of liquidity mining](https://youtu.be/C7wMuAKBs3A)** (sometimes called Yield Farming) ğŸ‘¨â€ğŸŒ¾ Hereâ€™s a quick refresher on what that is:\\n\\n> *Basically liquidity mining is a bit like lending. You lend your currency to provide liquidity to the market and you earn a share of the transaction fees. Because decentralized exchanges (or DEXs) use Automated Market Makers (or AMMs) which is just a smart contract that regulates trading, there is no central source of capital for liquidity. For that reason, liquidity providers are incentivized to lend their capital through receiving the trading fees that the end user paid to trade ğŸ’¸*\\n\\nOne thing I didnâ€™t go too much into detail about in that post (since it was already pretty dense) was how **impermanent loss** works. **[This post from Binance](https://trustwallet.com/blog/what-is-impermanent-loss)** explains the concept well, but simply put, you provide liquidity in pairs of assets and if one asset in the pair shifts in value, your liquidity rebalances to the maintain equal value. In doing so, you may replace your more valuable asset with the less valuable asset and the potential gain in value could be lost, this is called *impermanent loss* for reasons that will make sense to stock investors whoâ€™ve seen the value of a stock decreasing and decided to hold; this is because the losses are only realized if and when you sell. Only then do they become permanent ğŸ”’ But that doesnâ€™t mean you should never sellâ€¦\\n\\nYou see as I mentioned in the quote above, you are incentivized to provide liquidity by receiving a portion of the trading fees for the two assets in your pair. And the idea is that you expect to make far more off those fees â€” which can easily range from 20% to 2000% APY â€” than would you stand to lose if your impermanent losses become realized ğŸ§®\\n\\nTypically when I provide liquidity, I donâ€™t go too wild. Pairs of similar volatility or even pairs of stable coins face very low risk of impermanent loss. And pairs of high demand assets typically pay well enough to negate even large amounts of impermanent loss, provided that the reward is paid in an asset that is worthwhile ğŸ§ But then again this post is about not about good decisions, this is a Crypto Misadventureâ€¦\\n\\nA lot of people have made good money off of quick and risky investments in what are sometimes called *degen* (short for degenerate) yield farms ğŸ¥´ These farms spring up quickly, offer high rewards to liquidity providers, and often employ **[ponzi-scheme tokenomics](https://medium.com/unboundedthoughts/what-is-tokenomics-and-which-school-of-economics-would-crush-it-a796f7764273)**. Essentially, the earliest people into the pool will make the majority of the returns (often paid in the farm token), and will dump their coins on the people who join later, who may continue to make healthy gains, or may see their potential ROI drop to a level that they no longer feel is worthwhile.\\n\\nI donâ€™t have much interest in degen yield farming as Iâ€™m still pretty early in my journey towards financial independence and try not to expose myself to so much risk, but I do like to try things, and you canâ€™t always tell if a yield farm is truly too-good-to-be-true, until itâ€™s too late. If you reap your rewards and sell them on the way up, youâ€™ll make good money, if you vest them, you provide a lot of security to the long term value of the farm token and youâ€™re rewarded with a reasonable APY. All that said, when people start dumping their coins, the value will fall ğŸ“‰ So you have to make a calculation of whether or not the returns will remain worthwhile since more of a token thatâ€™s decreasing in value, could still be less money ğŸ§®\\n\\nFor this reason, I would consider every dollar invested in high return yield farms to be 100% gambling ğŸ° Now with that said, I know that some of you are out here investing in Gamestop, AMC, Dogecoin, and whatever penny stock or altcoin is expected to rocket up 600% the next couple months so there is a place for this kind of thing. Just promise me you wonâ€™t take out a line of credit against your mortgage and put it all into degen farming ğŸ™\\n\\nAlright so let me tell you exactly what happenedâ€¦\\n\\nI was experimenting with a yield farm called DFYN where for about a week, I had invested $28 in the USDC/DFYN liquidity pool, earning around 500% APY ğŸ”¥ In a very short time, I already earned more interest than I would have made in a year in a standard bank savings account. Again, weâ€™re talking tens of cents, but itâ€™s all relative right?\\n\\nDFYN, still appears to be a very stable and trustworthy project, but this week the talk of the town was **Iron Finance** ğŸ¤©\\n\\nIron had this idea to create an algorithmic stable coin called IRON that was pegged to 75% USDC and 25% TITAN (Ironâ€™s farm token). Iron is created by depositing USDC and burning TITAN. And when the user redeems IRON, they receive back their USDC and the required amount of TITAN is minted. The idea was so interesting that many people, **[including Mark Cuban](https://blogmaverick.com/2021/06/13/the-brilliance-of-yield-farming-liquidity-providing-and-valuing-crypto-projects/)** decided to become Liquidity Providers of TITAN ğŸ˜²\\n\\nOn Tuesday, I spotted the TITAN/USDC pool paying out over 900% APY and decided to take the money I had in my DFYN/USDC pair and throw it into there. Why not? As far as gambling goes, this felt like it would be pretty good odds, even if I get out in a few weeks, Iâ€™d have already made 30% or so on my investment ğŸ™Œ\\n\\nThe next day I spotted the ETH/TITAN pair at over 2000% and once again, I said â€œwhy not?â€ ğŸ¤·â€â™‚ï¸ I was gambling the same money for 500% as I was for 900% as I was for 2000% ğŸš€\\n\\nSo I put the $28 into the pool and went to work. At around 5pm, I saw on twitter that TITAN was plummeting in value and I quickly removed my liquidity ğŸ˜° By that point, I had realized a loss of the majority of my Ether in the pool. $14 had gone to around $2. Worse still, with no liquidity in the pools and rapid devaluation of the token, I could not swap my TITAN ğŸ˜–\\n\\nThose of you familiar with stock trading can think of this like trying to find a buyer when your ask price well above any bid (which keeps getting lower and lower in this case). Essentially in a supply and demand market, it became all supply and no demand ğŸ˜‘\\n\\nThis situation led to a funny screenshot that I posted on twitter where Zapper shows the value of my TITAN at $25.62 but the trade estimates its value at $0.51 USDC ğŸ¤« Needless to say, I have no choice now but to go long TITANâ€¦\\n\\n![](https://miro.medium.com/max/916/0\\\\*TFe_amIanj-KiPWN.png)\\n\\nNow this illustrates exactly why you need to be real with yourself about high return investments ğŸ’¸ The higher the return, the higher the risk. As Iâ€™ve already written, the reasonable returns in DeFi (largely because of the elimination of middlemen) are well above the reasonable returns in regular finance. Low risk endeavours can pay 10x the interest as a high interest savings account, and high risk endeavours can make Gamestop look like an index fund ğŸš€\\n\\nWith that said, Iâ€™ve learned my lesson and Iâ€™ll be doubling down on safer investments through my next round of experiments ğŸ¤“\\n\\nI did however put about $0.25 back into a TITAN poolâ€¦ I had to ğŸ‘‡\\n\\n![](https://miro.medium.com/max/1400/0\\\\*YJ4qzVrDGbyKeDjq.png)\\n\\nIf youâ€™re looking at that photo and thinking you should throw $100 or so inâ€¦ re-read this postâ€¦ ğŸ˜† Even though, **[Coindesk believes this was not a rug pull](https://www.coindesk.com/iron-finance-defi-titan-iron-price-drop)**, it was still an absolute hot mess. I will probably lose that $0.25 too but hey, *in for a penny, in for a pound*.\\n\\nI hope you found this story entertaining. If so, I can consider that lost money to be an investment into this blog. Iâ€™ll try to make sure that not every post is about losing money, but no promises ğŸ˜…\\n\\nUntil next time ğŸ‘‹ \\n Thumbs Up \\n \\n\\n\\n---\\n\\nDid you enjoy this content? Consider supporting me at thumbsupfinance.eth (Ethereum, ERC-20, BTC, Tezos, Nano)\\n\\nOr at thumbsupfinance.crypto for Polygon, Celo, Tezos, Nano, BTC and more.\\n\\nIn Canada I accept support via Wealthsimple Cash: $thumbsup\\n\\n\\n---\\n\\n**Rug** by **anggun** from **the Noun Project**\",\"timestamp\":1638939652,\"title\":\"Crypto Misadventures: (Im)permanent Loser\"},\"digest\":\"Ww77K17LLM_W2lCmCoMizwo-RwMvu2m7za8EQ9rbPmE\",\"authorship\":{\"contributor\":\"0x4d85e4F760fb58E380f02657AE5Aafb8bd010601\",\"signingKey\":\"{\\\"crv\\\":\\\"P-256\\\",\\\"ext\\\":true,\\\"key_ops\\\":[\\\"verify\\\"],\\\"kty\\\":\\\"EC\\\",\\\"x\\\":\\\"GJ07XkTvvtIz4d9Ecx3OEOJPuql-jBBatmCZtSQa1mQ\\\",\\\"y\\\":\\\"VQ76Ir62rbxC1ZlPCh3itlzDwNd1Ud8G7iWf1UGnP-c\\\"}\",\"signature\":\"H58urFCe9yZtfag2rungTnHzKRicjpR-w0kfkh8bVFmNlUFF99cHg_ITHMYp1MCKpjtW-UXqbR0_W18qohkUFA\",\"signingKeySignature\":\"0xb00d27d0a09453c722e310ee9d08db2c14f4a71028e34076fbec0336228b08d754346a54f5ac46cbd68881f35ed8344d82eced30e30a4d7910d682384451c00f1c\",\"signingKeyMessage\":\"I authorize publishing on mirror.xyz from this device using:\\n{\\\"crv\\\":\\\"P-256\\\",\\\"ext\\\":true,\\\"key_ops\\\":[\\\"verify\\\"],\\\"kty\\\":\\\"EC\\\",\\\"x\\\":\\\"GJ07XkTvvtIz4d9Ecx3OEOJPuql-jBBatmCZtSQa1mQ\\\",\\\"y\\\":\\\"VQ76Ir62rbxC1ZlPCh3itlzDwNd1Ud8G7iWf1UGnP-c\\\"}\",\"algorithm\":{\"name\":\"ECDSA\",\"hash\":\"SHA-256\"}},\"nft\":{},\"version\":\"12-21-2020\",\"originalDigest\":\"Ww77K17LLM_W2lCmCoMizwo-RwMvu2m7za8EQ9rbPmE\"}"